The `count` method reuses `list()` to get all tasks and then returns the length. For a large number of tasks, this is inefficient as it constructs an array of all task objects in memory just to get a count. A more performant implementation would iterate and count without creating an intermediate array.

```typescript
  async count(contextId?: string, state?: TaskState): Promise<number> {
    this.ensureInitialized();

    if (!contextId && !state) {
      return this.tasks.size;
    }

    let count = 0;
    for (const task of this.tasks.values()) {
      const contextMatch = !contextId || task.contextId === contextId;
      const stateMatch = !state || task.status.state === state;
      if (contextMatch && stateMatch) {
        count++;
      }
    }
    return count;
  }
```

